3. End-to-End Functional Flow (11 Steps)
Step 1: Supplier Onboarding
User navigates to "Suppliers" → "New Supplier".
Enters AADE Tax ID (ΑΦΜ).
System calls AADE API, auto-fills: Legal Name, DOY, Address, Status.
User adds: Display Name, Contacts, Phones, Emails.
User uploads Supplier Agreement (PDF). System stores it and indexes it for RAG search.
User uploads Supplier Catalog (Excel/PDF) and/or Product List (Excel).
System parses Catalog/Product List to pre-populate products and product_supplier_links.
User sets Code Normalization Rules (e.g., for Poimenidis, define the 03- stripping rule).
Step 2: Invoice / Offer Upload
User goes to "Invoices" → "Upload".
Selects Supplier from dropdown (or system auto-detects from document).
Selects Document Type: INVOICE or OFFER.
Uploads file: PDF, Image (PNG/JPG), or Excel/XML.
System stores file and creates Invoice record with status UPLOADED.
Step 3: Document Ingestion & Text Extraction
If PDF with text layer: Extract text using pdftotext -layout.
If scanned PDF/Image: Convert to PNG (pdftoppm -r 300), OCR with Tesseract (-l ell+eng, PSM 6).
If Excel/XML: Parse directly with SheetJS / XML parser.
Store extracted raw text in invoices.raw_text.
Step 4: Structured Data Extraction (The 3-Level Parser)

Goal: Turn raw text into a table of items (Code, Description, Qty, Price).

Level 1 — Hardcoded Parser:

System checks if Supplier has a dedicated TypeScript parser (e.g., poimenidis_parser.ts).
If canParse(rawText) returns true, execute parse(rawText) → return items.
If success, jump to Step 5.

Level 2 — Dynamic Regex Parser:

If no hardcoded parser exists, load parser_configs for this supplier.
Apply regex patterns stored in DB to extract table rows.
If confidence > threshold, return items.

Level 3 — AI Parser Generation:

If Level 1 & 2 fail, send sample PDF + raw text to LLM (Claude Sonnet via Abacus AI or Llama 70B).
Prompt: "Analyze this invoice and output a JSON array of items with keys: supplier_code, description, quantity, unit_price, line_total."
LLM returns JSON. System stores this as a new parser_config for future use (Learning).
If AI fails, set status to REVIEW_REQUIRED and alert user.
Step 5: Data Normalization
For each extracted line item, apply the Supplier's Normalization Rules.
Example (Poimenidis): supplier_code = "03-DCD996" → normalized_code = "DCD996".
Clean descriptions (remove extra spaces, standardize units).
Detect Barcodes (13-digit numbers) if present in description or separate column.
Step 6: Product Matching (The 4 Levels — NO PYLON CODE)

Goal: Link the invoice line item to an existing product via product_supplier_links.

Matching Hierarchy:

Barcode Match: If invoice_item.barcode matches product.base_barcode or product_supplier_link.supplier_code (if supplier code IS barcode). Confidence = 1.0.
Exact Code Match: invoice_item.normalized_supplier_code == product_supplier_link.supplier_code. Confidence = 1.0.
Normalized/Manufacturer Code Match: invoice_item.normalized_supplier_code == product_supplier_link.manufacturer_code. Confidence = 0.95.
Fuzzy/Partial Match: If description similarity > 0.85 (using embeddings or Levenshtein). Confidence = 0.7. Requires human approval.

Rules:

If match found, populate invoice_item.matched_product_id and set status MATCHED.
If NO match found, set status NEW_PRODUCT.
CRITICAL: PYLONCODE is NEVER used in this matching logic. It only appears in the Export phase.
Step 7: Product Creation (For NEW_PRODUCT items)
System shows user a "New Products Detected" screen.
For each unmatched item, system pre-fills:
Product Name: From invoice description (cleaned).
Supplier Code: invoice_item.normalized_supplier_code.
Manufacturer Code: invoice_item.normalized_supplier_code (if stripping rule applies).
Cost Price: invoice_item.unit_price.
Supplier: invoice.supplier_id.
User reviews and clicks Create Product.
System inserts into products table and product_supplier_links.
System updates invoice_item status to MATCHED.
Step 8: Cost Price Update
For all MATCHED items, system compares invoice_item.unit_price with product_supplier_links current cost.
Rule: The system DOES NOT automatically overwrite the master cost price.
Instead, it shows a "Pending Updates" list:
Product Name | Old Cost | New Cost (from invoice) | Supplier | Invoice Date
User reviews and clicks Apply Selected Updates.
System updates product_supplier_links cost, inserts record into product_cost_history, and logs action in audit_logs.
Step 9: Enrichment (The 5 Waves)

Trigger: After product creation or matching, system checks which fields are missing (image, barcode, full description, technical specs).

Wave 1 — Invoice XML/Embedded:

If invoice was XML, extract <ExtraData> or embedded product attributes. Store directly.

Wave 2 — Supplier Catalog / Product List:

Search uploaded Catalog/Product List files for the supplier_code or manufacturer_code.
If found, extract description, specs, images (if URLs). Store in product.

Wave 3 — Manual Enrichment:

User clicks "Enrich Product" and manually types/pastes data.
This data is marked as source: MANUAL and has highest precedence.

Wave 4 — AI-Assisted Parsing (from uploaded files):

If user uploads a product brochure PDF, AI (Vision) extracts specs and tables.
User reviews AI extraction before saving.

Wave 5 — Web Scraping (Last Resort):

If fields are still missing, system queues job for Crawl4AI.
Crawl4AI searches supplier website or Google for the manufacturer_code + manufacturer_name.
Scrapes images, descriptions, barcodes from 50+ e-shops.
Stores results with source: SCRAPED and confidence: LOW.
User must review and approve scraped data before it becomes "official".
Step 10: Human Review & Approval
Dashboard shows all invoices with status REVIEW_REQUIRED or MATCHED.
User clicks an invoice to see:
Extracted table side-by-side with matched product cards.
Yellow flags for low-confidence matches.
Red flags for NEW_PRODUCT items.
User can:
Drag-and-drop to re-match a line item to a different product.
Edit extracted values (price, quantity).
Approve the entire invoice.
Once approved, status changes to APPROVED. Cost updates (Step 8) can now be applied.
Step 11: Export to Pylon ERP
User navigates to "Export" → "New Export Job".
Selects:
Date Range (e.g., "Invoices from June 2026")
Supplier (optional)
Export Type: IMPORT (for new products) or UPDATE (for cost changes)
System generates XLSX:
IMPORT columns: ΠΕΡΙΓΡΑΦΗ, ΚΩΔΙΚΟΣ ΠΡΟΜΗΘΕΥΤΗ, ΚΩΔΙΚΟΣ ΚΑΤΑΣΚΕΥΑΣΤΗ, BARCODE, ΤΙΜΗ ΑΓΟΡΑΣ, ΦΠΑ, ΚΑΤΗΓΟΡΙΑ, ΚΑΤΑΣΚΕΥΑΣΤΗΣ.
UPDATE columns: PYLONCODE (if known), ΚΩΔΙΚΟΣ ΠΡΟΜΗΘΕΥΤΗ, ΝΕΑ ΤΙΜΗ ΑΓΟΡΑΣ, ΗΜΕΡΟΜΗΝΙΑ ΤΙΜΟΛΟΓΙΟΥ.
System auto-detects if a product has a PYLONCODE in the products table. If yes, it suggests UPDATE mode. If no, IMPORT mode.
User downloads XLSX and imports manually into Pylon ERP.
System logs export in export_logs and updates invoice status to EXPORTED.
